  "signature": "ed25519:b2c3d4e5f6a7b8c9d0e1f2a3b4c5d6e7f8a9b0c1d2e3f4a5b6c7d8e9f0a1b2c3",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/sqa-level2",
      "rationale": "All three FEA codes (FDA in-house, Ansys Mechanical 2021 R2, DePuy Synthes internal solver) are operated under documented software quality plans. Version control, regression testing, and release notes are maintained. FDA in-house code is subject to CDRH OSEL software governance. Ansys is a commercially validated code with ISO 9001 certification. DePuy Synthes internal code is subject to 21 CFR Part 820 QMS controls. Achieved Gradation 2 is appropriate for MRL 3 with Medium model influence."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/ncv-level2",
      "rationale": "Code verification was performed through benchmark problems including patch tests, single-element tests, and comparison against NAFEMS standard benchmarks for linear elastic beam bending and contact problems. All three codes demonstrated agreement within 0.5% of analytical solutions for the relevant element types (hexahedral C3D8 and tetrahedral C3D10). Cross-code comparisons among the three ensemble members further corroborate correctness of numerical implementation."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/disc-error-level2",
      "rationale": "Systematic mesh convergence studies were conducted for each ensemble model. Three mesh densities (coarse ~50k elements, medium ~150k elements, fine ~400k elements) were evaluated for each QoI. Richardson extrapolation was applied to estimate the grid convergence index (GCI). GCI values for stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement were all below 2% for the medium mesh, which was adopted as the production mesh. Achieved level 3 exceeds the required level 2, providing additional confidence in discretization adequacy."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/solver-error-level2",
      "rationale": "Iterative solver convergence was verified for each simulation run. Force and displacement residuals were required to fall below 1e-6 relative tolerance before accepting a solution increment. Contact force residuals were monitored separately and confirmed below 0.1 N at each converged increment. No solution divergence or spurious oscillation was observed across the 11-specimen ensemble. Solver log files are archived in the simulation data package."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/use-error-level2",
      "rationale": "Simulation execution followed documented standard operating procedures (SOPs) for each modeling environment. Independent peer review of model setup, boundary condition application, and post-processing scripts was performed by a second analyst at each organization. Discrepancies identified during peer review were resolved and documented before final results were accepted. Input decks and post-processing scripts are version-controlled and archived."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/model-form-level2",
      "rationale": "The FEA model employs a nonlinear quasi-static formulation with isotropic bilinear elastoplastic material models for Ti-6Al-4V screw and rod components, and linear elastic UHMWPE blocks per ASTM F1717 specification. Contact between screw and rod is modeled with penalty-based frictional contact (mu=0.2). The choice of continuum plasticity over crystal plasticity is appropriate for the bulk structural response of the implant at this scale. Model form assumptions are consistent with the literature and with the three-ensemble cross-check."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/model-inputs-level2",
      "rationale": "Material properties for Ti-6Al-4V (E=114 GPa, sigma_y=880 MPa, tangent modulus=1.14 GPa) were sourced from certificate-of-conformance tensile coupon data for the same material lot used in the bench specimens. UHMWPE block properties (E=1.0 GPa, nu=0.4) were taken from published ASTM F648 characterization data. Geometric inputs were derived from calibrated CMM measurements of the actual test specimens. Uncertainty in material properties was propagated through a parametric sensitivity study confirming QoI sensitivity below 3% per 5% property perturbation."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/test-samples-level2",
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were tested across two independent laboratories. All specimens were drawn from a single production lot with documented traceability to manufacturing records. Specimen dimensions were verified by CMM prior to testing. The sample size of 11 provides sufficient statistical power to characterize mean and standard deviation of each QoI and to compute the validation uncertainty metric u_val per ASME V&V 40 Eq. 7.1."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/test-conditions-level2",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted under a single ASTM F1717 standardized test condition (static compression-bending, 10 mm/min crosshead speed, ambient temperature). Only one loading condition was evaluated; the required level of 3 is not fully met because no variation in test rate, temperature, or saline environment was explored. This known gap is accepted because the COU is specifically scoped to ASTM F1717 standard conditions and the decision consequence is Medium. The shortfall is documented and accepted by the credibility assessment team as part of the overall risk-informed decision."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/equiv-inputs-level2",
      "rationale": "A formal input equivalency table was prepared mapping each experimental measurement (specimen geometry, material lot properties, fixture alignment, applied displacement) to the corresponding FEA model parameter. Discrepancies between nominal and as-measured values were quantified and incorporated into the model input uncertainty budget. All critical inputs (screw diameter, rod diameter, UHMWPE block modulus, inter-screw span) were matched within 1% between test and simulation."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/output-comparison-level2",
      "rationale": "Quantitative output comparison was performed using the ASME V&V 40 validation metric E/u_val for each QoI. For construct stiffness: E/u_val = 1.12 (< 1.96, pass). For yield force: E/u_val = 0.87 (pass). For force at 40 mm: E/u_val = 1.44 (pass). Percentage differences were 4.2%, 3.8%, and 6.1% respectively, all within the pre-established 10% acceptance bound. Full force-displacement curves from all three ensemble models are plotted against experimental corridors and archived. Achieved level 3 reflects the quantitative metric-based comparison with uncertainty propagation."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/qoi-relevance-level2",
      "rationale": "The three QoIs — construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement — are the quantities specified in ASTM F1717 as the primary mechanical performance metrics for spinal implant constructs. They are directly linked to the regulatory submission requirement to demonstrate structural adequacy of the pedicle screw system. The mapping from QoI to clinical risk (fatigue fracture, subsidence, revision surgery) is documented in the risk matrix and is consistent with the FDA guidance on spinal implant submissions."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/val-relevance-level2",
      "rationale": "The validation activities directly replicate the COU: the same non-cannulated 7.5 mm screw geometry, the same ASTM F1717 test configuration, and the same three QoIs are used in both validation and the intended regulatory submission. The FEA ensemble was not recalibrated after initial model setup — predictions were made a priori relative to the second laboratory's data. The validation domain (static compression-bending of Ti-6Al-4V pedicle screw construct in UHMWPE blocks) is fully coincident with the COU domain, providing high relevance."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment team reviewed all 13 V&V 40 factors for COU1 (non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw, ASTM F1717 static compression-bending). Twelve of thirteen factors met or exceeded their required credibility levels. The single shortfall — Test conditions (achieved level 2 vs. required level 3) — reflects the deliberate scope limitation to a single standardized test condition, which is consistent with the ASTM F1717 regulatory pathway and the Medium decision consequence. The validation metric E/u_val passed all three QoIs (stiffness: 1.12, yield force: 0.87, force at 40 mm: 1.44), all below the 1.96 threshold. Percentage differences were 4.2%, 3.8%, and 6.1%, all within the pre-established 10% acceptance bound. The three-laboratory FEA ensemble cross-check and N=11 experimental sample provide robust statistical grounding. The provenance chain is complete from raw experimental data through post-processing to the validation metric computation. The credibility assessment team unanimously accepts the FEA modeling framework as sufficiently credible for the intended regulatory use, with the Test conditions shortfall documented and accepted as risk-informed.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
